  "prompt": "Are ductile metals also malleable?",
  "response": "Yes, ductile metals are generally also malleable. Ductility refers to a metal's ability to be stretched into a wire, while malleability refers to a metal's ability to be hammered or rolled into thin sheets. Both properties are related to the ability of metal atoms to slide past each other without breaking the metallic bond. Metals like gold, silver, and copper exhibit both ductility and malleability, making them versatile for various applications in manufacturing and construction.",
